=C2=A0does not solve the accredited-investor problem, but it is fine as far=
 as it goes, and there are lots of examples. (Special-purpose vehicles to b=
uy unicorn stock, or  large bank-run funds to let their private-wealth clie=
nts get access to unicorn stock.)Another approach is =E2=80=9Cwhat if we so=
ld you a derivative on the stock.=E2=80=9D This is a fairly=C2=A0popular ap=
proach; private-company employees and venture capitalists sometimes use for=
ward sales to sell their stock, in the future, to outside investors. Or the=
re are  unicorn structured notes? Again there are legal issues to consider:=
 For one thing you do not solve the accredited-investor problem; for anothe=
r thing, it is not always clear that the sellers of the forwards=C2=A0(empl=
oyees, VCs) are=C2=A0allowed=C2=A0to enter into them under the terms of the=
ir employment or shareholder agreements. But, sure, a thing.Another approac=
h is =E2=80=9Cwhat if we sold you a derivative on the stock, but on the blo=
ckchain.=E2=80=9D This has the advantage of, like, you can pretend that it=
=E2=80=99s less illegal than it is, because people sometimes think that sec=
urities laws don=E2=80=99t apply on the blockchain. People don=E2=80=99t be=
lieve this as much as they used to, but a few years ago =E2=80=9Cderivative=
s on private company stock but on the blockchain=E2=80=9D was  briefly sort=
 of a thing.=C2=A0But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look. Non-fungible tokens are hot righ=
t now. The way a non-fungible token works is:=09I create a work of art, or =
destroy a work of art, or make a joke, or do something else.=09I sell you a=
 digital proof, enshrined permanently in an open blockchain, that you have =
paid me for that work of art or whatever I did.=09That is the entire transa=
ction: You get =E2=80=9Cownership=E2=80=9D of whatever I sold you in the fo=
rm of that digital proof on the blockchain, but (in the general case) no le=
gal rights to the thing.Are there NFTs of the Brooklyn Bridge? You=E2=80=99=
d better believe it. What do you get when you buy an NFT of the Brooklyn Br=
idge? You get proof, on a blockchain, that you bought the NFT of the Brookl=
yn Bridge. What is that worth to you? Very little really, because if you bu=
y a Brooklyn Bridge NFT it is uncomfortably clear that you are being made f=
un of. With other NFTs it=E2=80=99s a bit less clear!What I propose is Unic=
ornCoin:=09There=E2=80=99s some hot giant tech startup, Unicorn Inc., that =
gets a lot of buzz and raises money at a $40 billion valuation.=09I mint 40=
 billion UnicornCoins.=09=E2=80=9CAs Unicorn Inc. goes up in value, each Un=
icornCoin will also gain value, I guess, whatever,=E2=80=9D I say.=09You bu=
y UnicornCoins.=09Unicorn Inc. announces new cool things.=09People notice t=
hat and UnicornCoin goes up.=09The system works.=09Unicorn Inc. goes public=
 at an $80 billion valuation.=09Has the price of UnicornCoin doubled? Man, =
I have no idea, none of this is anything, but does it=C2=A0feel=C2=A0like s=
omething?I confess that I am inspired by NFTs, and I guess by Tether, but a=
lso by  the SHIB cryptocurrency, which, through the awesome power of pure n=
onsense, seems to track something like =E2=80=9Chow much attention are peop=
le online paying to Elon Musk getting a Shiba Inu?=E2=80=9D When Musk tweet=
s about getting a Shiba Inu dog, SHIB goes up. Is it worth more?=C2=A0Is th=
ere a robust arbitrage mechanism to ensure that the price of SHIB tracks th=
e cuteness of Musk=E2=80=99s Shiba Inu? Does SHIB confer any ownership righ=
ts to Musk=E2=80=99s dog? Are there cash flows from the dog that are securi=
tized into SHIB? No, absolutely not, it is nothing, it is a pure online jok=
e, but when Musk tweets about his Shiba Inu people are like =E2=80=9Coh I r=
emember that there=E2=80=99s an online joke token=C2=A0about this=E2=80=9D =
and they buy SHIB and it goes up. It has a market capitalization of $10 bil=
lion. It=E2=80=99s  up 216% this week because of a Musk tweet. This isn=E2=
=80=99t my fault! I don=E2=80=99t make this stuff up! This is a real thing =
that is happening!All I am saying is that if I sold you a crypto token that=
 was called =E2=80=9CStripeCoin=E2=80=9D and I said =E2=80=9Cthis is a toke=
n on the stock of Stripe=E2=80=9D you might say =E2=80=94=C2=A0because you =
are reading Money Stuff, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might say =E2=80=9Cwait ho=
w is the value of the token linked to the value of Stripe=E2=80=9D and I wo=
uld say =E2=80=9Chahahaha it absolutely isn=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D But my hypo=
thesis is that not everyone is as skeptical and literal-minded as you are, =
and some people would just go buy StripeCoin=C2=A0when they had nice though=
ts about Stripe and sell StripeCoin=C2=A0when they had sad thoughts about S=
tripe and buy a whole lot of StripeCoin=C2=A0when Stripe went public,=C2=A0=
and it would at least directionally end up being a sort of a proxy for Stri=
pe stock. And everyone would get what they came for, which is a convenient =
way to gamble on people=E2=80=99s feelings about Stripe.=C2=A0Anyway here=
=E2=80=99s a much more complicated thing:The meme-ification of ownership an=
d the wild acceleration of private startup valuations have led us to this m=
oment where a former VC firm associate has built a crypto marketplace desig=
ned for =E2=80=9Cfantasy startup investing,=E2=80=9D where users spend real=
 money buying fake=C2=A0shares =E2=80=94 in NFT form, of course =E2=80=94 o=
f real startups.The game, which launches out of closed beta today, is calle=
d Visionrare and founders Jacob Claerhout and Boris Gordts see a way to tak=
e the gamification of investing to its furthest end, mimicking the appeal o=
f fantasy sports leagues and giving users a way to compete with friends by =
betting on startups they think will be successful. Users can bid on NFT sha=
res of hundreds of different startups at auction and compete to build the b=
est performing fake portfolio. =E2=80=A6The game aims to simplify the compl=
exity of venture capital in an auction format that=E2=80=99s tied to the ac=
tual fundraising cycles of the startups and their real world performance. V=
isionrare auctions off 100 serialized =E2=80=9CVisionShares=E2=80=9D per fu=
nding round, one at a time for each startup, with bids starting at $5. Once=
 a user accumulates a certain number of shares (at least five) they can joi=
n a league and compete with other users through a fantasy-like experience, =
moving up and down a leaderboard while competing for a share of the collect=
ive value of the VisionShares based on the performance of their own portfol=
io.No, boo, I don=E2=80=99t care about this, dream bigger and dumber.
