<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tether</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A (the?) main move in finance goes lik=
e this:</p><ol type=3D"1" style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: =
40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a risk=
y thing. It will be worth a lot of money in some states of the world and le=
ss money in some other states of the world. Perhaps it will be worth $200, =
or $100, or $50. Perhaps it is trading at $100 now.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">You divide that risky thing into=C2=A0<em>junior </em>and=
<em>=C2=A0senior</em> claims. When you find out how much the risky thing is=
 worth, you pay off the senior claims first, and then the junior claims get=
 whatever=E2=80=99s left. Perhaps you issue $50 of senior claims and promis=
e to pay them back=C2=A0$50,[1] and then you issue $50 of junior claims and=
 promise to pay them back whatever=E2=80=99s left. If the thing ends up bei=
ng worth=C2=A0$200, the senior claims get $50 and the junior claims get $15=
0 and triple their money; if the thing ends up being worth $50, the senior =
claims get $50 and the junior claims get $0 and lose all their money. The j=
unior claims are extra-risky =E2=80=94=C2=A0more risky than just the origin=
al risky thing itself =E2=80=94=C2=A0while the senior claims are, in this h=
ypothetical scenario, completely safe. The senior claimants put in $50 and =
get back $50 no matter what.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There ar=
e variations on this move; principally, you can divide the thing into more =
than two tranches of=C2=A0claim. (Very safe super-senior claims get paid fi=
rst, quite safe senior claims get paid next, then somewhat risky mezzanine =
claims, then quite risky equity claims.) Also you can compose this move: Yo=
u can divide a bunch of things into junior and senior claims, bundle a set =
of junior or senior claims together, and then slice that bundle into junior=
 and senior claims.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most of what happens in=
 finance is some form of this move. And the reason for that is basically th=
at some people want to own safe things, because they have money that they d=
on=E2=80=99t want to lose, and other people want to own risky things, becau=
se they have money that they want to turn into more money. If you have some=
thing that is moderately risky, someone will buy it, but if you slice it in=
to things that are super safe and things that are super risky,=C2=A0<em>mor=
e=C2=A0</em>people might buy them. Financial theory <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25266856.280691/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVka=
WEub3JnL3dpa2kvTW9kaWdsaWFuaSVFMiU4MCU5M01pbGxlcl90aGVvcmVt/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBdb8c4578" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">suggests that this is impossible</a> but virt=
ually all of financial practice disagrees.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Some examples. A=C2=A0<em>business=C2=A0</em>is a risky thing; its fu=
ture cash flows might be high or low. It slices those cash flows into senio=
r claims (debt) and junior claims (equity). Some people (banks, etc.) want =
to lend the business money in exchange for a safe senior claim on its futur=
e cash flows. Other people (venture capitalists, etc.) want to give the bus=
iness money in exchange for a lottery ticket that it will one day be worth =
a lot.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A <em>house</em> can go up or =
down in value; it may end up being worth more or less than you pay for it. =
But if you get a mortgage, your bank puts up (say) 80% of the money and has=
 a senior claim on your house. If your house loses 19% of its value, and yo=
u sell it, you will be sad; your down payment evaporated. But the bank will=
 be fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually the bank doesn=E2=80=99t=
 care because it has pooled a bunch of those mortgages (senior claims on ho=
uses) into a mortgage-backed security,=C2=A0cut that security into tranches=
 (senior claims, mezzanine claims, junior claims) and sold the tranches on =
