<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SOFR loan</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a company and you take out =
a loan, the loan will usually have a floating rate, and periodically the ra=
te will reset to (1)=C2=A0Libor, the London interbank offered rate, a bench=
mark interest rate published each day,=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>(2) a credit=
 spread that is fixed in the loan contract.[6] The contract might say =E2=
=80=9Ceach quarter the interest rate will reset to 3-month Libor plus 225 b=
asis points.=E2=80=9D That number =E2=80=94=C2=A0225 basis points, 2.25% =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is fixed in the contract and added to 3-month Libor every th=
ree months; it is the credit spread. People will describe the loan=E2=80=99=
s pricing as being =E2=80=9CL+225,=E2=80=9D Libor plus 225 basis points.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a company you want your cred=
it spread to be lower rather than higher, both because it saves you money =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0each basis point of credit spread costs you $100 of interest=
 per year per million dollars you borrow =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also as a matte=
r of pride. A tighter credit spread means that you are a better credit, tha=
t lenders are more confident in you, that you are doing a better job of man=
aging risk, etc.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Libor is going away =
though. Libor is in theory the rate at which big banks can borrow unsecured=
 for some specified period of time (3 months, etc.); in practice they don=
=E2=80=99t do that much of that borrowing and they have some history of lyi=
ng about the rates. So it is being replaced by more market-based rates. In =
the U.S., the main replacement is SOFR, the Secured Overnight Financing Rat=
e, which is the rate that big institutions=C2=A0pay to borrow overnight sec=
ured by Treasury securities. (There are various ways to turn SOFR, an overn=
ight rate, into a one- or three- or whatever-month rate, using for instance=
 curves constructed from SOFR futures.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I=E2=80=99ve been hearing about this transition for years, but it was al=
ways in the future. Companies kept getting loans, and they kept being index=
ed to Libor, despite increasingly impatient talk from regulators. Now that =
is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25266856.280691=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDUvd2Fsa2=
VyLWR1bmxvcC1nZXR0aW5nLWZpcnN0LWxldmVyYWdlZC1sb2FuLWZ1bGx5LXRpZWQtdG8tc29mc=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5b94ff6a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">finally changing</a>:</p><bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Real estate lender Walker &amp; Dunlop =
Inc. became the first company to announce a U.S. leveraged loan sale that f=
ully embraces regulators=E2=80=99 preferred replacement for the London inte=
rbank offered rate, a milestone in the shift away from Libor that could fin=
ally unleash a flood of copycats.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The $600 =
million seven-year loan will be benchmarked to the Secured Overnight Financ=
ing Rate, according to a person familiar with the matter. Libor is being ph=
ased out because of the rigging scandal that came to light a decade ago, an=
d SOFR is a leading candidate to fill its role.</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Paula Seligson <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25266856.280691/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDUvanBtb3JnYW4tcy1zZWFsLW9mLWFwcHJ=
vdmFsLWdpdmVzLWh1Z2UtYm9vc3QtdG8tbGlib3ItaGVpci1zb2Zy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB45f40dc3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">writes</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The announcement of a new loan offering tied to the Secured Overnight Fi=
nancing Rate, or SOFR, is a huge moment for Wall Street. It raises hopes th=
at the leveraged-loan market is finally making a real attempt to ditch Libo=
r, like other parts of the financial markets -- such as derivatives and inv=
estment-grade bonds -- where far more progress has been made over the past =
few months, or even years.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank marketi=
ng the loan, JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., has enormous clout. Its embrace of S=
OFR on behalf of a customer could finally break the logjam that=E2=80=99s p=
revented borrowers from using SOFR -- the rate regulators want as the U.S. =
replacement for Libor, the disgraced benchmark that can no longer be tied t=
o new loans and other financial products sold after New Year=E2=80=99s Eve.=
 Existing loans will be able to reference Libor through mid-2023.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal =E2=80=9Cshould help to set a precedent and=
 encourage other lenders to quickly move to offering more SOFR loans,=E2=80=
=9D said Tom Wipf, chairman of the Alternative Reference Rates Committee, t=
he Federal Reserve-backed body guiding the transition.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">For months, finance pros have waited for SOFR deals in the $1.2=
 trillion leveraged loan market. Instead they were met with silence, and no=
thing to suggest the new rate was going to be battle tested in time. Now, w=
ith Tuesday=E2=80=99s deal, there=E2=80=99s suddenly greater confidence tha=
t other companies will step forward with similar offerings.</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine. But here is a small technical problem. =
SOFR is a bit lower than Libor: SOFR is a rate for essentially risk-free lo=
ans secured by Treasuries, while Libor incorporates banks=E2=80=99 credit r=
isk. =E2=80=9CRight now,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/25266856.280691/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDYvcHJpY2luZy1sb2Fucy1vZmYtbGlib3ItaGVpci1sb29rcy1zaW=
1wbGVyLXRoYW4tbWFya2V0LWZlYXJlZA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53459778" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>writes Seligson</a>,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cone-month Libor is 8.6 basis points, or=
 just 2.7 basis points above its SOFR counterpart=E2=80=9D (which is 0.059%=
), but historically the difference has been somewhat wider. Let=E2=80=99s s=
ay that the correct long-term difference is 10 basis points.[7] In the long=
 run =E2=80=94=C2=A0over the course of a seven-year loan printed today =E2=
=80=94 SOFR will average out to be 10 basis points lower than Libor.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the loan is no less expensive for the b=
ank to make, the company is no less risky, etc., just because it says =E2=
=80=9CSOFR=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9CLibor.=E2=80=9D So the pricing=C2=
=A0of the loan should be the same. Which means that, if SOFR is 10 basis po=
ints lower than Libor, then you need to add 10 basis points to the spread t=
o make the pricing correct. A company that could have gotten a loan at L+22=
5 will instead get a loan at SOFR+235. This will cost the same amount: SOFR=
 is 10 basis points lower than Libor, so SOFR+235=C2=A0<em>equals=C2=A0</em=
>L+225.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except that finance is kind o=
f dumb sometimes. If you are the treasurer of a company, you have worked ha=
rd to get your credit spread down to 225 basis points. When a bank tells yo=
u that now it=E2=80=99s 235, you=E2=80=99ll be mad. =E2=80=9CBut this is a =
higher spread applied to a lower base so actually it=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94,=E2=
=80=9D the bank starts to say, but you don=E2=80=99t want to hear it. You w=
ant 225.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if you are an investor i=
n loans you are looking at some spreadsheet of comparable loans, and they a=
re all at L+225, and you see this one is at +235 and you say =E2=80=9Cthat =
number is too high=E2=80=9D and you are flummoxed. Things are supposed to b=
e comparable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So there is lovely dumb solut=
ion which is to put the 10 basis points somewhere else. Instead of saying "=
the price is SOFR plus a spread,=E2=80=9D you say =E2=80=9Cthe price is SOF=
R plus a spread plus a spread adjustment.=E2=80=9D[8]=C2=A0<a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25266856.280691/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDYvcHJpY2luZy1sb2Fucy1vZmYtb=
Glib3ItaGVpci1sb29rcy1zaW1wbGVyLXRoYW4tbWFya2V0LWZlYXJlZA/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cC53459778" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">Seligson</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Walker &amp; Dunlop will pay SOFR plus a =E2=80=9Ccredit spread ad=
justment=E2=80=9D of 10 basis points, along with some additional interest k=
nown as a spread that hasn=E2=80=99t yet been determined. (Investors may st=
ill push for some changes in the terms of the deal, which is due to be sold=
 in the middle of next week.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cre=
dit spread adjustment is meant to turn SOFR into something approximating Li=
bor, so investors and companies can see the spread and understand the loan=
=E2=80=99s pricing quickly.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Right now a lot of loans are indexed to Libor and a few (almost none, b=
ut more are coming) are indexed to SOFR, and it would break everyone=E2=80=
=99s brains if some companies were quoted on a spread to Libor and others w=
ere quoted on a spread to SOFR, so instead some companies are quoted on a s=
pread to Libor and others are quoted on a (fully comparable) =E2=80=9Csprea=
d to SOFR, but if it were Libor.=E2=80=9D I love it.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">If Libor does go away entirely, I assume that the =E2=80=9Ccredit=
 spread adjustment=E2=80=9D will also go away, and companies will just get =
loans at SOFR plus some spread and be quoted at =E2=80=9CSOFR + whatever=E2=
=80=9D; everyone will use SOFR so everything will be comparable.=C2=A0But m=
aybe not! Who wants to be the first company to get rid of the adjustment an=
d have a higher nominal spread? Maybe it will persist forever as a vestigia=
l vanity item; maybe in 30 years junior law firm associates will cut and pa=
ste a loan agreement and ask their partner =E2=80=9Cwhy is this Credit Spre=
ad Adjustment here=E2=80=9D and the partner will say =E2=80=9Coh, nobody kn=
ows, that=E2=80=99s just in every loan agreement, you gotta adjust the cred=
it spread.=E2=80=9D</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cel=
lpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
